    transcript: "They 've got allowances on National Sh orts for young stuff here , but ...They 've got allowances on Nash ar shorts for the old stuff here , but ...You don 't understand .- You don 't understand .When the overall cost of employment , as an employer ,increases .It is always the youngest people to get hit the hardest .So even if there is a bit of a national assuranceAllow ance for people under 25 whatever it is . It 's not enough to offsetthe overall increase in this , but the minimum wage hike is the worst part . Actually , there was a guided and amazing breakdown of this on X S today .about exactly why hiking minimum wage .I got into a ding - d ong with someone about it .Of course !We all won 't .Everyone 's wages to be higher .The only time that that happens is when employersare making bigger .Because the profits ...is where the budget for more .employment and higher wages comes from and without those profits .You don 't get more jobs , or wage growth .",
    summary: 'Main topics:\n' +
      '- How increases in the overall cost of employment affect different age groups, and whether allowances for young workers suffice.\n' +
      '- The impact of minimum wage hikes, including a reference to a breakdown seen on social media and a personal dispute about the issue.\n' +
      '- The argument that wage growth and job creation hinge on higher profits for employers.\n' +
      '\n' +
      'Key points and conclusions:\n' +
      '- The speaker argues that when the overall cost of employment rises, the youngest workers are hit hardest. Even with allowances for under-25s, these measures do not fully offset the increases, so the policy is insufficient to protect youth employment.\n' +
      '- They view the minimum wage hike as the worst part of the equation. A detailed breakdown they saw on X/S is cited to challenge the idea that raising the minimum wage automatically boosts wages for all.\n' +
      '- The speaker contends that wage growth and job creation occur only when employers have larger profits. Without higher profits, more jobs and higher wages are unlikely, regardless of minimum wage policy or other allowances.\n' +
      '\n' +
      'Conclusion:\n' +
      '- There are no concrete action items or decisions stated. The speaker emphasizes a skepticism about the efficacy of minimum wage hikes alone and underscores the condition that profits are necessary to fund employment growth and higher wages.',
